•Yinka Odumakin LAGOS – Mrs Joe Okei-Odumakin, wife of the Afenifere spokesman, Yinka Odumakin, has confirmed the death of her husband from complications arising from of COVID-19. Odumakin, it was learnt, died at the Lagos State University Teaching Hospital isolation centre. His wife, Mrs Joe Okei-Odumakin, confirmed this to The PUNCH on Saturday. Our correspondent was told that a delegation of Yoruba leaders were on their way to the residence of Afenifere leader, Ayo Adebanjo, to break the news to him. The wife said, “A part of me is gone. A part of me is gone. He fought hard at the intensive care unit. Pray for me to survive this. My love is gone. “He was OK before. Even on March 10 he was still attending meetings. He was recovering yesterday but he died this morning. I am at the intensive care unit. A part of me is gone.” •Yinka Odumakin LAGOS - Spokesman of pan-Yoruba socio-political group Afenifere Yinka Odumakin has died of complications from COVID-19. The activist had been on ventilator at a treatment centre in Lagos, Qed.ng learned. Qed.ng was informed that he had serious underlining conditions including diabetes, lung-related issues and a mild stroke first… In "Top Stories" By Lucy Osuizigbo   Lagos  -  Rights activists on Saturday described Late Dr Frederick Fasehun, Founder of the Oodua Peoples Congress (OPC), as an irrepressible social crusader and dedicated nationalist. The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the late Fasehun, also an active member of National Democratic Coalition (NADECO),… In "News" The Oodua People’s Congress may go into partisan politics if the conditions that warranted its setting up are not in place in the country in the next few months. The National Coordinator of the OPC and Aare Ona Kakanfo of Yorubaland, Iba Gani Adams, dropped the hint at the 25th… In "Politics"